{
  "id": "hadamard-maximal-determinant",
  "title": "Hadamard Maximal Determinant",
  "domain": "Math - Linear Algebra",
  "attribution": {
    "authors": [
      "Siddhartha Mahajan (Lossfunk)"
    ],
    "reviewers": ["Dr. Ankan Pal (BITS Pilani)"]
  },
  "origin": "In 1893, Jacques Hadamard posed an interesting question: given an n x n matrix whose entries are all +1 or -1, what is the largest possible value of its determinant? It took over a century of effort for finding exact answers for some small matrices (n up to 22). For n = 23 and beyond, much less is known. The best values found so far come from computer searches by Orrick, Solomon, Dowdeswell, and Smith in 2003, using hill-climbing and simulated annealing. Most of those records have stood unchallenged for over 20 years.",
  "instance": "For any value of n from the records table below, construct an n x n matrix (M) consisting of only +1 and -1 such that the absolute value of the determinant (|det(M)|) is strictly larger than the current known maximum value for that particular n. For example, the record for n = 23 is |det(M)| = 2,779,447,296,000,000. To claim a new record, submit a single matrix that beats this value. Each n is an independent challenge and you only need to improve one.",
  "scoring": {
    "summary": "Each submission is scored on how close its determinant gets to the theoretical upper bound for the chosen n.",
    "metrics": [
      {
        "name": "Bound ratio",
        "description": "The primary score is |det(M)| / B(n), where B(n) is the theoretical upper bound (Hadamard, Barba, Ehlich-Wojtas, or Ehlich depending on n mod 4). This gives a percentage between 0% and 100%. Higher is better."
      },
      {
        "name": "New record",
        "description": "If |det(M)| strictly exceeds the previously best known value for that n, the submission is flagged as a new record and the submitter is credited on the leaderboard."
      },
      {
        "name": "Tiebreaker",
        "description": "If two submissions achieve the same determinant for the same n, the earlier submission ranks higher."
      }
    ],
    "note": "Submissions that match but do not beat the current record are still accepted and scored. Getting to 93% of the theoretical bound is meaningful even without setting a new record."
  },
  "submissionExample": "{\n  \"n\": 23,\n  \"claimed_det\": 2779447296000001,\n  \"matrix\": [\n    [1, -1, 1, ...],\n    [-1, 1, 1, ...],\n    ...\n  ]\n}\n(The claimed_det shown above is illustrative.)",
  "verification": "We compute the exact integer determinant of your matrix using sympy (no floating point). The submission is accepted if the matrix is n x n, all entries are +1 or -1, and |det(M)| matches your claimed_det. Every valid submission receives a score of 100 * |det(M)| / B(n), where B(n) is the theoretical upper bound for that n.",
  "bounds": [
    {
      "label": "n mod 4 ≡ 0",
      "name": "Hadamard bound",
      "formula": "n^(n/2). Tight when a Hadamard matrix exists."
    },
    {
      "label": "n mod 4 ≡ 1",
      "name": "Barba bound",
      "formula": "(2n-1)^(1/2) * (n-1)^((n-1)/2). See Barba (1933)."
    },
    {
      "label": "n mod 4 ≡ 2",
      "name": "Ehlich-Wojtas bound",
      "formula": "(2n-2) * (n-2)^((n-2)/2). See Ehlich (1964) and Wojtas (1964)."
    },
    {
      "label": "n mod 4 ≡ 3",
      "name": "Ehlich bound",
      "formula": "Derived from eigenvalue analysis of M^T M. See Ehlich (1964)."
    }
  ],
