  "suggestedApproach": [
    {
      "title": "Pick an n",
      "body": "Any row in the records table. n = 23 is the smallest open case and has the most literature."
    },
    {
      "title": "Random start",
      "body": "Generate a random {+1, -1} matrix. Compute its determinant."
    },
    {
      "title": "Hill-climb",
      "body": "Flip entries that increase |det|. Cofactor expansion lets you update the determinant cheaply (O(n^2) per flip) without recomputing from scratch."
    },
    {
      "title": "Simulated annealing",
      "body": "Accept some determinant-decreasing flips to escape local maxima. This is exactly how the Orrick et al. 2003 records were set."
    }
  ],
  "agentPrompt": "I want you to find a {+1, -1} matrix of size n = 23 whose determinant (in absolute value) exceeds 2,779,447,296,000,000 (the current record, factored as 2^22 x 3 x 5^6 x 67 x 211). Use hill-climbing with simulated annealing: start from a random +/-1 matrix, repeatedly flip entries that increase |det(M)| using cofactor updates, and randomly perturb when stuck in a local maximum. Run many restarts and report the best matrix found. Output the matrix as a JSON array of arrays, and report the determinant value.",
